One of my patients sent me this video from @jillianmichaels about the new drug semaglutide. She has a gross misunderstanding of obesity and why people fail to lose weight along with how these trials are run.

I forgot to add in a quick segment about the fear of thyroid cancer. It is a very rare type of thyroid cancer that rats are predisposed to. There is no signal that this occurs in humans.

I have many patients on this medicine who finally feel they have a normal appetite. It’s not that they lack willpower, it’s because it’s physiology! Let me know what you think of the video.

node.text:
Got a few questions in my QnA about lowering blood cholesterol levels with diet. Here is a post I made from before that gives the gist.

With some simple changes I’m usually able to lower my patient’s cholesterol levels by around 10 to 40% depending on their current diet.

There has been a massive spike in cholesterol levels due to fads such as bullet proof coffee and putting a lot of butter and coconut oil in cooking and in foods. A small amount of these fats are likely not harmful but of course people go to the extremes and douse their foods with them. Coconut oil and butter are high in saturated fats that down regulate your liver’s ability to recycle the LDL cholesterol. Remember that saturated fat is an umbrella term and there are multiple saturated fatty acids. The ones in butter and coconut oil specifically have LDL cholesterol increasing properties. Furthermore other types of fats actually up regulate your liver’s ability to recycle LDL cholesterol. These fats are generally in nuts and seeds. So you have a double whammy when you actually replace the butter and coconut oil with these other types of fats.

The next thing I usually do is swapping out your non-fibrous carbohydrate options with more soluble fiber carbohydrate options. The soluble fiber actually binds some of the cholesterol in your intestines which then you eventually excrete. This also increases your liver’s ability to recycle the LDL cholesterol that’s in your blood. The bottom right is a bowl of lentils.

what about dietary cholesterol like eggs and shrimp? There is an effect there but the effect is not as large as these first two options. For that reason I focus on these first then add the other later if need be. There will be people to try this and barely fudge their cholesterol levels. This is because they are likely genetically prone and no dietary or lifestyle change will have much of an effect. For those people drugs may be necessary.

i’m sure there will be a few commenters who try to mansplain cholesterol to me despite me being a lipidologist. LOL!

#plantbased #cholesterollowering #cholesterol

I'd like a wake up call. @DrNadolsky Artificial sweeteners aren't stopping your weight loss, fasting isn't necessary to lose weight, and starvation mode isn't real.'.

node.text:
I think this guy just probably woke up!

Have posted often about artificial sweeteners. They do not inhibit fat loss.

You do not need to fast to lose weight. It’s simply another way to lower your intake.

Starvation mode, how most people define it, is a myth. Our metabolisms do decrease as we diet and lose weight. That’s totally normal. What doesn’t happen is a complete adaptation to a low calorie diet to where we aren’t losing anymore weight UNLESS we got to a size where that’s standard diet that metabolic rate. Go to NIH body planner to see right about where your basal metabolic rate is. You can then see what it would be after losing x amount of weight if you want. Also the great thing is that our metabolisms go up once we stop dieting and go to “maintenance”. This is where we are eating as many calories as we burn. ❤️❤️ stay woke my friends.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 16, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of text that says 'Dr. SpInn Nadolsky @DrNadolsky "I've been in a calorie deficit for two years and have not lost weight!" -someone who was not in a calorie deficit'.

node.text:
I have to keep repeating this because every week I see a few people say they have been in a calorie deficit for a long period of time with no weight loss…. And it’s just not true.

It’s true they are probably trying. It’s true that they feel like they are constantly dieting. It’s true that that may be counting their calories. It’s true that they used some calculator that says they should be in a calorie deficit. What’s not true is that they are in a calorie deficit. If they were, they would be losing weight over a period of time (water fluctuations do occur).

Weight loss (what we really want is fat loss) occurs when you’re eating fewer calories than you burn. If you’re not losing weight/fat over the period of let’s say 2-4 weeks, it’s probably safe to say you’re not in a calorie deficit. Read the first paragraph in this post again.

There are a ton of variables to go through of why you can’t achieve this calorie deficit (hunger, inaccuracies in measuring, etc) but either way you’re not in a calorie deficit. This doesn’t mean you’re a bad person or an idiot or to blame etc. It’s just physiology.

So if this is you, it may be time to diagnose the issue at hand of why you aren’t able to do it. Or maybe it’s time to stop dieting. I can’t answer that without a history and knowing a lot more. ❤️oh and it’s not the damn carbs or insulin.

node.text:
Hey folks it’s not the carbs. It’s not the fat. It’s not the insulin. In order to lose fat and keep it off, you must eat fewer calories than you burn. This doesn’t mean you have to count calories. It doesn’t mean you have to go low carb or low fat. Either can work though.

So what should you do? Here are some general guidelines:

1. Eat mostly non-processed foods. I would suggest mostly vegetables and fruits and legumes with lean protein.

2. Drink mostly water, coffee, tea, and diet soda (if wanted but of course not needed). Basically drinks without calories.

3. Start finding which foods keep you fuller and satiated. Some may find higher carb starchy foods like potatoes work well. Some may find that lower carb higher fat foods work better (avocados). Some may enjoy a mix.

4. If still struggling, do a dietary audit and track how many calories you’re getting in. Weigh your food and figure out if portions are an issue.

5. Be conscious of bites and licks and tastes between meals. Sneaky calories. Adding butter and oils to pasta. It’s okay to do this but just be conscious of the added calories. Sauces can also add up.

Of course this alone may not be perfect but it’s a good start. I use the NIH bodyplanner tool to look at calorie recommendations but remember it’s just a starting point. We have our RP app and templates if you want us to tell you what to do. Can click on my link in bio and use coupon: START10

There are individuals who are clearly anti-VAX who will never be convinced with even the best dialogue possible. However there are many people on the fence… and I have even discussed with many of them in my DM‘s. I’ve been very happy to see many who are on the fence get vaccinated after some good discussion and understanding the worry and fears.

Had I called them are idiots for not getting vaccinated it probably wouldn’t have gone the same way. Anyway I bring this up because there are many healthcare professionals who are well-meaning but post in a way that probably isn’t conducive to getting people to change their minds about vaccinations. Many of the same people discuss the futility of shaming those with obesity. There is obviously overlap with this as well. Of course obesity and not getting vaccinated are not the same but there is some overlap. At least enough of some overlap to make this analogy LOL. Anyway, was just thinking about this yesterday❤️
